snippet.textDisplay: MatPat, I don't know if this helps, but I think I figured out something that might help you with future theories. In the introduction of FNaF VR Help Wanted, it tells you "...and while its true that some stories associated with our name were loosely based on actual events, the majority of them were total fabrications from the mind of a complete lunatic"  I think SpringTrap is based off of Glitchtrap. Let me explain. We know all of the Animatronics and everything that happened in the FNaF games were based on "real" events that happened and someone who saw those events made the games from what they saw(like with your theories on Oswald). So, if he saw an employee dressed in a golden rabbit suit, he probably saw Glitchtrap, just not in a way he's seen in the game. Its kind of like what Scott did. He made a game about Animatronics in a pizza restaurant that's based on Chuck E Cheese. We see regular Animatronics, he sees haunted Animatronics. Everyone else sees Oswald's Dad, Oswald sees Glitchtrap. And in the game, it says" the majority of them were total fabrications from the mind of a complete lunatic". This could mean its talking about Oswald. That he's gone insane

snippet.textDisplay: When Matt said the animatronics were super advanced, it made me realise just how amazing it is that they can walk around at all. Real life animatronic bands like CHUCK e. Cheese and the Rockafire Explosion were never able to reach that level of technology. They're big, clunky and controlled by hydraulics which makes it impossible for them to walk around, so the fact that the animatronics in these games can do this at all is insane.

snippet.textDisplay:
Matt, I'm not sure if we say this enough, but I'll choose to only speak for myself here:

I love your FNAF theories. I love that you allow me to make sense of all the twisted threads that this series puts me through. If not for your theories, I'd probably have given up understanding at the second game because I simply don't have time to dig into this stuff, which would've made me sad and frustrated since I knew that the lore went deeper then I'd found (as proven by you later).

And to give you an idea of just how awesome these are: I was able to connect with a couple of friends' kids (11 and 13, respectively) by chatting with them about Purple Guy and the Bite of '87. According to their parents, they'd never seen their kids that excited to talk to a grown-up before. And I haven't been able to play the games since the second one came out.

Keep doing what you do, Matt. Your theories are doing more good then you'll ever know.
